TD Ameritrade: Orders Go to Venues That Pay Most

headline.main-hed: TD Ameritrade Executive Says Orders Go to Venues That Pay Highest Fees
headline.deck: Comments Come as Senate Panel Asks Whether 'Maker-Taker' Fee Structures Are Best for Investors

article-body.p: A top executive for retail broker TD Ameritrade Holding Corp. told a Senate panel Tuesday that the firm routinely sends customer orders to trading venues that provide the brokerage with the highest payments.

The comments by TD Ameritrade Vice President Steven Quirk sparked questions from the Senate panel about whether the firm focuses more on reaping income than executing buy and sell orders that are in the best interest of its clients. Critics say brokers that regularly send orders to trading outlets offering the best payments can miss out on better trading opportunities elsewhere, including more favorable prices for investors.

The hearing by the Senate Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations, led by Sen. Carl Levin (D., Mich.), focused on whether such conflicts of interest are eroding investors' confidence in the stock market.
"We've got to rid our market of conflicts of interest to the extent that it's humanly possible if we are to restore investor confidence," Mr. Levin said.

highlight.link: Congress Turns a Spotlight on High-Speed Trading
Regulators Weigh Curbs on Trading Fees

article-body.p: A TD Ameritrade spokeswoman later said the firm takes its "execution duties very seriously." "It is the top priority when considering the routing of clients' orders," she said.

Regulators and law-enforcement officials have launched sweeping investigations into computerized markets, with an eye on whether some sophisticated firms enjoy advantages over others and whether high-speed trading can destabilize markets. Securities and Exchange Commission Chairman Mary Jo White said in a recent speech that while "technology can and has greatly increased the efficiency of our markets" it can also "allow severe problems to develop very quickly."

Mr. Quirk, responding to questions from Mr. Levin, said that in the first quarter of 2014, his firm routed millions of clients' limit orders—those designed to trade only at a specific price—to just two trading venues, one run by BATS Global Markets and another run by Citigroup Inc.'s electronic-trading unit Lava Trading.

The two trading venues, BATS's EDGX exchange and LavaFlow, provide among the highest payments in the market, about 35 cents per 100 shares traded, experts say. Mr. Quirk told the Senate panel that TD Ameritrade earned roughly $80 million in such payments in fiscal 2013.

TD Ameritrade takes into account a variety of other factors to determine how to route customer orders, including which venues provide the best result for its clients, Mr. Quirk said. The final factor, he said, is the size of the payment.
Mr. Levin asked Mr. Quirk whether the firm's routing decisions "virtually always led you to route orders to the markets that paid you the most."
"Virtually, yeah," Mr. Quirk replied.

Mr. Levin said he found it to be "a pretty incredible coincidence" that the firm always decided that the best result for clients was nearly always found at the trading venues that offered the highest payments.

The issue broadly concerns fees and payments stock exchanges and other trading firms give to brokers that send orders their way. Retail brokers are typically paid to route a certain amount of clients' orders to specific firms, an arrangement known as payment for order flow. Exchanges also provide payments for orders that help make trades happen, while charging a fee to firms on the other side of the trades.
Brokers regularly send limit orders to exchanges, looking to get payments for helping to make trades happen, while avoiding the fees for firms that "take" orders.

This "maker-taker" fee plan, which is used by nearly all U.S. stock exchanges, has come under scrutiny, and SEC officials are weighing whether to launch a pilot program to curb it. Thomas Farley, president of NYSE Group, which runs the New York Stock Exchange, told the subcommittee that he favors a marketwide ban on maker-taker arrangements. Mr. Farley said the fees and payments, which are profitable for NYSE, worsen conflicts of interest among brokers and make the market overly complex.

University of Notre Dame finance professor Robert Battalio, who testified before the subcommittee, earlier this year co-published a paper arguing that retail brokers such as TD Ameritrade often route client orders in ways that boost payments they receive, potentially harming clients.

Mr. Battalio, referring to his study, said such routing decisions typically send client orders to exchanges that have long waiting times relative to other exchanges, because other traders are also vying to get the payments. If the market moves away from the price the client hoped to trade at, the client might not trade at all, he said. An order sent to an exchange with a shorter waiting time, meanwhile, would have been more likely to get executed.

Bradley Katsuyama, chief executive of IEX Group Inc., a trading venue that claims to address certain conflicts of interest in the market, told the Senate subcommittee that he believed the problem could potentially be solved if regulators or lawmakers required brokers to disclose more information about how they route client orders, among other things.
"Disclosure and transparency will help people make the right decision" about how they trade, he said. "Right now a lot of it is opaque."
